 and decline of traditional systems in which poet-scholars were patronized by religious institutions, landowners, and local kings; the anatomy of changes in textual practices, genres, styles, poetics, themes, tastes, and audiences; and the role of literature in the politics of social reform, gender, and incipient nationalism. The work concludes with a discussion of the most striking literary development of the time—the emergence of the Tamil novel.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aLiterature and societyzIndia, SouthxHistoryy19th century. 0aTamil literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Literature. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 4aAsian Studies : India and South Asian Studies. 4aLiterature : Literary History. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Hindu Studies. 7aHISTORY / Asia / India & South Asia.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438432014423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438432014/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles